Second Interview
Introduction & Context Setting 

Interviwer: Thank you for taking the time today. Before we begin, I just want to confirm -Are you comfortable with me recording this conversation for academic purposes?
P02: Yes, that’s completely fine.
Interviwer: Great. To start off, could you briefly describe your role and what a typical working day looks like for you?
P02: Sure. As a Sales Executive, my day mainly revolves around clients responding to inquiries, giving project explanations, showing plot options and sometimes coordinating site visits. On busy days, especially weekends- it's almost non-stop client interaction.
Interviwer: Would you say your role is more reactive or proactive?
P02: Mostly reactive. Clients come with questions  and we have to respond immediately. There’s very little time to prepare in advance.
 Daily Workflow Deep Dive 
Interviwer: Walk me through a typical client interaction from start to finish.
P02: Usually, a client comes in or contacts us online. First, I try to understand their budget and preferred location. Then I suggest relevant projects, explain pricing and show them available plots.
Interviwer: At what point do challenges usually start?
P02: When they ask specific questions. For example:
•	“Is this plot still available?” 
•	“What’s the exact road width here?” 
•	“What developments are planned nearby?” 
That’s when I need very accurate, up-to-date information.
Interviwer: And do you usually have that information immediately?
P02: Not always. That’s where things slow down.
Information Access & Breakdown 
Interviwer: Let’s focus on that. What happens when you don’t have immediate answers?
P02: I have to check multiple sources. And honestly, that’s one of the biggest issues in our workflow.
Interviwer: Can you describe your process step by step?
P02: Yes, typically:
1.	Check internal documents (PDFs, brochures) 
2.	Look at spreadsheets for availability 
3.	Ask colleagues nearby 
4.	Check WhatsApp groups 
5.	Call the site office if needed 
Interviwer: That’s quite a few steps. How long does that take?
P02: Sometimes a few seconds, sometimes several minutes. But even a 1-minute delay feels long when a client is waiting.
Interviwer: I’d like to understand the challenges in more depth. Could you elaborate on the biggest problems?
P02:
1. Fragmented Information Ecosystem
There is no integrated system. Everything exists in silos documents, messages, verbal updates.
2. Lack of Data Ownership
It’s often unclear which department is responsible for updating what. So outdated information stays in circulation.
3. Real-Time Accuracy Gap
Sales depends on real-time data, but updates can be delayed by hours or even days.
4. Informal Knowledge Dependency
Some of the most accurate information comes from experienced colleagues—not official systems. That’s risky.
5. Cognitive Overload
We are expected to remember:
•	Dozens of projects 
•	Hundreds of plots 
•	Pricing variations 
•	Development plans 
It’s unrealistic without proper tools.
6. Repetition & Redundancy
We repeatedly answer the same client questions without having a standardized response system.
7. Lack of Visual Clarity
Most data is text-based. But clients—and even sales staff—need visual understanding.
8. Slow Internal Tools
When systems lag, it directly impacts client experience.
9. Weekend Pressure Spike
Peak demand happens when systems are under the most stress.
10. Trust Erosion
If a client catches even one inconsistency, they start doubting everything.
 Emotional & Performance Impact 
Interviwer: How do these challenges affect you personally?
P02: It creates stress. You feel like you should know everything, but the system doesn’t support you.
Interviwer: Does it affect your confidence?
P02: Definitely. Especially in the beginning. Even now, if I’m unsure about something, I hesitate.
Interviwer: What about performance metrics?
P02: It affects conversion rates. A confident, smooth interaction can close a deal. A hesitant one can lose it.
Interviwer: Can you recall a specific situation?
P02: Yes. Once I told a client a plot was available, but it had already been booked. When I corrected myself, the client lost trust and didn’t proceed further.

 Learning Curve & Training Gaps 
Interviwer: Looking back, what were the biggest gaps in your training?
P02:
•	No structured onboarding 
•	No centralized learning resource 
•	No simulation or practice scenarios 
Interviwer: How did you compensate for that?
P02: Trial and error. Observing seniors. Learning from mistakes.
Interviwer: What would an ideal onboarding look like?
P02:
•	Interactive training modules 
•	Visual project maps 
•	Real-life client scenarios 
•	A searchable knowledge base 
Technology & AI Opportunities 
Interviwer: Let’s imagine an ideal system. What would it include?
P02: A single dashboard with:
•	Live availability 
•	Auto-updated pricing 
•	Interactive maps 
•	Searchable FAQs 
Interviwer: And AI?
P02: AI could:
•	Answer instant queries 
•	Suggest plots based on client needs 
•	Provide quick comparisons 
•	Reduce dependency on memory 
Interviwer: What’s the one feature that matters most?
P02: Accuracy. If the system is accurate, everything else follows.
 Final Reflection 
Interviwer: If you had to summarize everything in one sentence?
P02: The job is manageable-but the lack of a reliable information system makes it unnecessarily difficult.
Interviwer: And one change that would make the biggest impact?
P02: A centralized, real-time information platform.
Interviwer: Thank you. This has been extremely valuable.
P02: Happy to help. I hope your project goes well.

